ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The 1st reported U.S. outbreak of _S. enterica_ serotype Agona was traced
to animal feed made with infected imported fishmeal in 1972. This serotype,
which rarely causes infections in humans, is capable of infecting the same
foods that other _Salmonella_ serotypes commonly do, such as meat, eggs,
fish and poultry.
_Salmonella_ Agona organisms, maintained in a suitably dry environment, can
remain viable for extended periods. When re-hydrated in the right
conditions, these organisms can grow, multiply and potentially cause infection.
The 1998 12 USA state outbreak of _S. enterica_ serotype Agona was linked
to a toasted oat cereal. Because of this, Malt-O-Meal Inc. recalled up to 3
million pounds of cereal USA-wide. The cereal manufacturer asked grocers to
pull from their shelves the Malt-O-Meal brand of plain Toasty-Os and
Toasted Oats, as well as plain toasted oat cereals sold at 38 supermarket
chains under various brand names.
A recent recall of powdered infant formula in Ireland was related to
_Enterobacter sakazakii_. - Mod.LL]
